Part 1

Get the full dataset out of the site. Your code should end up with a tibble of a bit more than 600 rows and 9 columns. Make sure you take the time to convert each column to the right type so not all are character columns.

simple <- read_html("https://epfl-exts.github.io/rental-scrape") 

scrape_adress <-
simple %>% 
  html_nodes(".sec-info .address") %>% 
  html_text()

scrape_price <-
simple %>% 
  html_nodes(".price .float-right") %>% 
  html_text()

scrape_objecttype <-
simple %>% 
  html_nodes(".bg-text .object-type") %>% 
  html_text()

scrape_floor <-
simple %>% 
  html_nodes(".floor strong") %>% 
  html_text()

scrape_living_space <-
simple %>% 
  html_nodes(".living-space strong") %>% 
  html_text()

scrape_rooms <-
simple %>% 
  html_nodes(".rooms strong") %>% 
  html_text()

scrape_usable_surface <-
simple %>% 
  html_nodes(".usable-surface strong") %>% 
  html_text()

scrape_availability <-
simple %>% 
  html_nodes(".availability strong") %>% 
  html_text()

scraped_tibble <-
  tibble(object_type = scrape_objecttype, address = scrape_adress, floor = scrape_floor, living_space = scrape_living_space, rooms = scrape_rooms, usable_surface = scrape_usable_surface, availability = scrape_availability, price = scrape_price) %>% 
    
  mutate(floor = as.numeric(floor), living_space = as.numeric(str_remove(living_space, " m2")), rooms = as.numeric (rooms), usable_surface = as.numeric(str_remove(usable_surface, " m2")), price = as.numeric(str_remove(price, " CHF")), address_cp = substr(substring(address, regexpr(", 1", address) +2),0,4))

  scraped_tibble

Part 2

Create a scatterplot showing how price evolves with living space of a flat.

tibble_livingspace <-
scraped_tibble %>%
  filter(living_space > 0, price > 0)


tibble_livingspace %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = living_space, y = price)) +
  geom_point( color = "#3B88B7") +
  labs(title = "Price evolution with living space", 
       y = "Price (CHF)", x = "Living Space (m2)")

Part 3

Create a bar plot showing the number of properties by postcode. Is this agency more “active” in certain areas?

tibble_postcode <-
  scraped_tibble %>%
  filter(address_cp > 0) %>% 
  count(address_cp, name = "rent_id") %>% 
  arrange(desc(rent_id)) %>% 
  head(10)

  ggplot(data = tibble_postcode,
       mapping = aes(x = address_cp, 
                     y = rent_id)) +
  geom_col(color = "#3B88B7", fill = "#3B88B7") +
  labs(title = "Top 10 address CPs by agency listings", y = "Number of listings", x = "Address CP")

In the following plot we can observe the top 10 postcodes respect to the number of properties for rent. The agency shows higher activity on CPs 1206 & 1205 respectively.

Part 4

Create a more complex scatterplot, showing how price evolves with living space of the flat by postcode and by floor. You can use colors and/or facets to make the categories visible.

tibble_facetplot <-
scraped_tibble %>%
  filter(living_space > 0, price > 0, floor > 0, floor < 7)


tibble_facetplot %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = living_space, y = price, color = address_cp)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(vars(floor),ncol = 3) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  labs(title= "Price evolution with living space", subtitle = "By address CP & address floor #", y = "Price (CHF)", x = "Living Space (m2)")

Part 5

Can you see any trends for listings with addresses only available on demand? Are they more expensive or less? Bigger living space? Higher floor?

Boxplot or violin plots work really well to compare distributions of values between groups. So use one for each of the three questions above.

tibble_advanced_address <-

  scraped_tibble %>%
    mutate(address_available = if_else(str_detect(address, pattern = "Address on request"),"Address on request","Address available")) 


tibble_advanced_address %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = address_available, y = price)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_boxplot(fill= "#3B88B7", color= "#222A35") +
  labs(title = "Price (CHF) by address listing type", y = "Price (CHF)", x = "Address listing type")

The median of price is higher for listings with address on request.

tibble_advanced_address %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = address_available, y = living_space)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_boxplot(fill= "#3B88B7", color= "#222A35") +
  labs(title = "Living space (m2) by address listing type", y = "Living space (m2)", 
       x = "Address listing type")

The median of living space is higher for listings with address on request.

tibble_advanced_address %>% 
  filter(floor < 15) %>%   # to reduce two points that are only making plot more diffitul to read
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = address_available, y = floor)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_boxplot(fill= "#3B88B7", color= "#222A35") +
  labs(title = "Floor # by address listing type", y = "Address Floor #", x = "Address listing type")

The median of floor # is very similar for the two types of listings in scope.

Part 6

In this question, use the same groups as above: flats whose addresses are only available on demand versus other flats. Make a table summarising group size, median, average, standard-deviation, minimum and maximum of the variable price per square-meter (expressed in CHF/\(m^2\)).

Have a look at the statistics. What is your impression, is there a difference in price per square-meter for these 2 groups of flats, and in what direction?

After writing down your initial impression, use a t-test to statistically compare the average price per square-meter for these types of flats.

What is your conclusion, is your initial impression statistically supported by the results of the t-test?

tibble_advanced_address %>% 
  mutate(price_per_m2 = price / living_space) %>% 
  group_by(address_available) %>% 
  summarise(group_size = n(), median = median(price_per_m2, na.rm = TRUE), 
            mean = mean(price_per_m2, na.rm = TRUE), standard_dev = sd(price_per_m2, na.rm = TRUE), 
            minimum = min(price_per_m2, na.rm = TRUE), maximum = max (price_per_m2, na.rm = TRUE))
tibble_t_test_final <-
  tibble_advanced_address %>% 
  mutate(price_per_m2 = price / living_space)

No huge differences observed on medians of price/\(m^2\). Mean shows that apparently flats with address available are slightly more expensive on average, however, this could be heavily impacted by extreme values (highest values or lowest values) in the dataset.

my_t_test <-
  tibble_t_test_final %>% 
  filter(price > 0, living_space >0) %>% 
  t_test(formula = price_per_m2 ~ address_available,
  order = c("Address available", "Address on request"),
  conf_level = 0.95)
  my_t_test

T-test result shows a p-value of 0.31, which is not strong enough to reject the null hypothesis: we can conclude both type of listings have a similar price/\(m^2\).

Part 7

Do the same as in part 6, but now looking at the variable price (expressed in CHF).

Compare the results of price per square-meter with those for price. Are there differences between the results? How would you interpret these differences?

tibble_advanced_address %>% 
  group_by(address_available) %>% 
  summarise(group_size = n(), median = median(price, na.rm = TRUE), mean = mean(price, na.rm = TRUE), standard_dev = sd(price, na.rm = TRUE), minimum = min(price, na.rm = TRUE), maximum = max (price, na.rm = TRUE))

By looking at price only, median is much larger for addresses on request. Nonetheless, when considering surface (median of price/\(m^2\)), as in shown on part 6, the gap between both groups is less significant. Similar conclusion for mean of price/\(m^2\) vs mean of price. The standard deviation shows values are more spread on the address available group. The same observation is valid when looking at maximum of price/\(m^2\) and price (for address available group).

Part 8

Convert a subset of 30 addresses to latitude and longitude using an API and plot them on a map using {ggmap} (or {leaflet} if you cannot get {ggmap} to work).

tibble_30_addresses <-
  tibble_advanced_address %>% 
  filter(address_available == "Address available", ) %>% 
  arrange(desc(living_space)) %>% 
  head(30)

vector30 <- tibble_30_addresses %>%
  pull(address) %>% 
  str_replace_all(" ", "+") %>% 
  str_replace(", ", "+") %>% 
  str_replace_all(",", "") %>% 
  paste0("+CH")

results_30_adresses <-str_glue("https://geocode.xyz/{vector30}?json=1") %>% 
  map(GET) %>% 
  map(content)

coordinate_points <-
  results_30_adresses %>% 
  map_df(magrittr::extract, c("longt", "latt")) %>% 
  mutate(longt = as.numeric(longt), latt = as.numeric(latt))

Geneve_area <- c(left = 5.855600, bottom = 46.085028, right = 6.327956, top = 46.345574)
 
Zurich_map <- get_stamenmap(bbox = Geneve_area, zoom = 12) 
ggmap(Zurich_map) +
  geom_point(data = coordinate_points, aes(x = longt, y = latt), color = "red") +
  labs(title = "Sample of 30 addresses from the rental website", subtitle="Geneve area", x="Longitude", y="Latitude")
